Asian Citrus, Cheung Kong, Cnooc: Hong Kong Equities Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-10-03T01:14:30Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-10-03/asian-citrus-cheung-kong-cnooc-hong-kong-equities-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  fell 2.3 percent to 17,592.41. The Hang
Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H shares of
Chinese companies, declined 3.9 percent to 8,917.36.  Railway companies: China postponed construction of 80
percent of its railway projects, pending clarification of
government policies, 21st Century Business Herald reported,
citing an unidentified person close to the railway ministry.  CSR Corp. (1766 HK), a mainland train maker, tumbled 9.1
percent to HK$2.80.  China Railway Group Ltd. (390)  (390 HK), a builder
of the nation’s railroads, tunnels and bridges, sank 7.1 percent
to HK$1.58.  Asian Citrus Holdings Ltd. (ACHL)  (73 HK): The owner and operator
of orange plantations in China has ties to  Chaoda Modern
Agriculture Holdings Ltd. (682)  (682 HK), according to a Hong Kong
stock exchange filing. Chaoda’s Chairman Kwok Ho and Chief
Financial Officer Andy Chan were accused by Hong Kong’s
financial secretary of  insider trading , according to a notice
released by the tribunal on Sept. 28. Asian Citrus tumbled 28
percent to HK$3.62.  Chaoda Modern Agriculture Holdings Ltd. (682 HK): The
Chinese vegetable supplier said it delayed releasing its annual
results to “include additional audit procedures” after a
report was issued by Anonymous Analytics. The stock was last
traded on Sept. 26 before being suspended.  Cheung Kong Holdings Ltd. (1)  (1 HK): The developer controlled
by billionaire  Li Ka-shing  sold about 35 new apartments at its
La Splendeur development on Oct. 1, Hong Kong-based Wen Wei Po
reported, citing unidentified people. The stock declined 1.7
percent to HK$85.60.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  (883 HK): The Chinese oil company’s plan to buy
Argentine crude producer Pan American Energy LLC from BP Plc is
at risk of collapse, according to a person with knowledge of the
matter. Political opposition may stop a unit owned by Cnooc and
 Argentina ’s billionaire Bulgheroni family from buying BP’s 60
percent stake for $7.1 billion, the persons said.  Gome Electrical Appliances Holding Ltd. (493 HK): The
electronics retailer said it put on hold its plans to form a
property venture after considering factors including current
market conditions. The stock tumbled 22 percent to HK$1.83.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
 John McCluskey  at 
 j.mccluskey@bloomberg.net . 